# Documentation Maintenance

Docs are lean and single-source-of-truth. When a change affects any area below, update the matching doc **in the same change** — do not leave docs stale, and do not create new doc files when an existing one covers the topic.

**Keep updates lean.** Match the doc’s existing tone, structure, and bullet length. State architecture-level facts in `docs/`; put file names, function names, and step-by-step implementation detail in the relevant app README (e.g. sync lifecycle in `apps/mobile/README.md`, not a long bullet in `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`). Prefer tightening a line over adding a paragraph.

| Change | Update |
| --- | --- |
| Architecture, sync model, app boundaries, hosting | `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` |
| Env vars, setup steps, tooling, keys | `docs/SETUP.md` + relevant `.env.example` |
| Migrations, tables, RLS, storage buckets | `docs/DATABASE.md` |
| AI endpoints, models, prompts, rate limits, wire contract | `docs/AI.md` |
| Backend endpoints/auth/deploy | `apps/backend/README.md` |
| Mobile structure or data flow | `apps/mobile/README.md` |
| Web dashboard | `apps/web/README.md` |
| Supabase workflow/keys | `supabase/README.md` |

Also keep in sync:

- AI wire contract: `apps/mobile/lib/ai/client/types.ts` ↔ `apps/backend/internal/extract/types.go` (manual mirror — changing one requires changing the other and noting it in `docs/AI.md`)
- New/changed shared shapes → `packages/types` Zod schemas first, then consumers
- If a cursor rule in `.cursor/rules/` states something this change makes false, fix the rule too

Never resurrect deleted docs (PROJECT_CONTEXT.md, docs/SETUP_GUIDE.md, etc.) — git history has them.
